    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait u said gremlin? lol what do u mean by that. anyway, i'm worried about the corners especially since it's a bathroom and it might get humid. how do i make sure the corners don't crack or pull apart once the mud dries?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Gremlin,\" I said, just a little chuckle in my voice, because sometimes the process of drywalling feels like trying to wrangle a particularly stubborn, muddy goblin! Those corners, especially in a humid bathroom, are where the real trouble starts. You need to treat those corners like a fortified wall against the dampness.\n\nFirst, when you're taping the inside and outside corners, make sure you're building up the mud in a gradual slope, not a sharp, sudden angle. If you hit a hard 90-degree corner with a thick blob of mud, it's going to crack like a dried-out piece of old jerky. Instead, use your taping knife to create a gentle, curved transition where the two surfaces meet. Think of it like a slow, deliberate ramp leading into the corner.\n\nFor extra reinforcement in high-humidity areas, you can consider using a fiberglass mesh tape over the seams before you even start mudding. This gives the mud something strong to grip onto, preventing that dreaded pull-apart. It’s like giving your mud a little exoskeleton! Then, when you apply the compound, make sure you're pressing it firmly into the mesh.\n\nAnd don't forget",
      "source": "target",
